0:11:40.26,000 --> 0:11:42,000
at the same time, a mechanical engineer,

282
0:11:42.26,000 --> 0:11:44,000
a geographer

283
0:11:44.26,000 --> 0:11:46,000
and a mathematician and so on, a physicist?

284
0:11:46.26,000 --> 0:11:49,000
Well actually I started, oddly enough,

285
0:11:49.26,000 --> 0:11:51,000
studying stock market prices.

286
0:11:51.26,000 --> 0:11:53,000
And so here

287
0:11:53.26,000 --> 0:11:56,000
I had this theory,

288
0:11:56.26,000 --> 0:11:58,000
and I wrote books about it --

289
0:11:58.26,000 --> 0:12:,000
financial prices increments.

290
0:12:00.26,000 --> 0:12:02,000
To the left you see data over a long period.

291
0:12:02.26,000 --> 0:12:04,000
To the right, on top,

292
0:12:04.26,000 --> 0:12:07,000
you see a theory which is very, very fashionable.

293
0:12:07.26,000 --> 0:12:1,000
It was very easy, and you can write many books very fast about it.

294
0:12:10.26,000 --> 0:12:12,000
(Laughter)

295
0:12:12.26,000 --> 0:12:15,000
There are thousands of books on that.

296
0:12:15.26,000 --> 0:12:18,000
Now compare that with real price increments.

297
0:12:18.26,000 --> 0:12:2,000
Where are real price increments?

298
0:12:20.26,000 --> 0:12:22,000
Well, these other lines

299
0:12:22.26,000 --> 0:12:24,000
include some real price increments

300
0:12:24.26,000 --> 0:12:26,000
and some forgery which I did.

301
0:12:26.26,000 --> 0:12:28,000
So the idea there was

302
0:12:28.26,000 --> 0:12:3,000
that one must be able to -- how do you say? --

303
0:12:30.26,000 --> 0:12:33,000
model price variation.

304
0:12:33.26,000 --> 0:12:36,000
And it went really well 50 years ago.

305
0:12:36.26,000 --> 0:12:39,000
For 50 years, people were sort of pooh-poohing me

